    "body": "# Why AI Automation in Go-to-Market Requires More Than Predictable Workflows\n**TL;DR:** A recent industry discussion highlights the challenge of applying AI automation to go-to-market strategies, suggesting that judgment-dependent tasks like narrative positioning may require different approaches than repeatable asset creation.\n## The Nuance Problem in GTM Automation\n\nA conversation circulating among AI practitioners raises an interesting point about the limits of automation in go-to-market workflows.\n\nThe core observation: AI tools can excel at predictable, repeatable work—think templated asset creation or standardized content generation. But GTM strategy often involves something harder to automate: judgment calls about positioning and narrative tailored to specific customers.\n\nAs one practitioner noted, large language models like Claude operate as \"world models\" that need to be steered with appropriate context. This isn't a flaw—it's simply how these systems work. The implication is that successful AI deployment in complex GTM scenarios may depend less on the model itself and more on how it's directed.\n\nThis tension has reportedly led some in the space to develop specialized tooling designed to handle the messier, judgment-intensive aspects of sales and marketing work.\n\n**The takeaway for teams evaluating AI automation:** Consider where your workflows fall on the spectrum between repeatable tasks and nuanced decision-making. The former may be ripe for automation today; the latter may require more thoughtful implementation—or purpose-built solutions.",
